## What is a Web Crawler?

A **web crawler** (also called a Spider or Spiderbot) is an automated program that systematically browses the internet to discover and download web content.

Think of it like a librarian walking through an infinite library:
- They start from a known shelf (Seed URLs)
- Read each book (web page)
- Note every reference cited inside (links on the page)
- Follow those references to find new books
- Keep a log of what they've already read (URL Seen Detector)
- Repeat indefinitely

---

## Common Use Cases

### 1. Search Engine Indexing
Companies like Google, Bing, and Yahoo use web crawlers to scan and index billions of web pages. Without crawlers, search engines would have no data to serve search results from.

- **What it does:** Scans pages, extracts text/metadata, stores them in a search index
- **Why it matters:** Users get relevant results only because crawlers have already visited those pages

### 2. Data Mining & Market Research
Businesses crawl competitor websites, e-commerce platforms, and news sites to gather:
- Pricing data (competitor prices)
- Product listings
- Sentiment analysis (news headlines, reviews)
- Academic research datasets

### 3. Web Archiving
Services like the **Wayback Machine** (archive.org) crawl and snapshot websites over time so you can go back and see what a website looked like in the past. This is valuable for journalism, legal discovery, and historical research.

