## Requirements

### Functional Requirements
| Requirement | Why It Matters |
|---|---|
| Crawl and store web pages | Core purpose — must be able to fetch and persist content |
| Extract links from pages | To discover new pages to crawl (web graph traversal) |
| Avoid duplicate content | Wastes storage and compute if we store the same page twice |
| Support HTML (extendable to other formats) | Start simple, but design for PDFs, images, etc. later |

### Non-Functional Requirements
| Requirement | Why It Matters |
|---|---|
| **Politeness** | Don't overwhelm a single server with too many requests. Respect `robots.txt`. Good crawlers space out requests per domain |
| **Prioritisation** | Not all URLs are equally important. High-value pages (e.g. BBC homepage) should be crawled more often than obscure pages |
| **Scalability** | Must handle billions of URLs per month across distributed machines |
| **Fault Tolerance** | If one worker crashes, the system should recover and not lose progress |
| **Extensibility** | Design so you can later add image downloading, PDF parsing, etc. |

