## Capacity Estimation

These calculations show how big the system needs to be.

### Given Assumptions
- Pages to crawl per month: **1 billion** (10⁹)
- Average page size: **2.5 MB** (2.5 × 10⁶ bytes)

### Monthly Storage
```
Storage/month = 10⁹ pages × 2.5 × 10⁶ bytes/page
              = 2.5 × 10¹⁵ bytes
              = 2.5 Petabytes/month
```

### Yearly Storage
```
Storage/year = 12 × 2.5 × 10¹⁵
             = 3 × 10¹⁶ bytes
             ≈ 30 Petabytes/year
```

### 5-Year Total Storage
```
Storage (5 yrs) = 5 × 3 × 10¹⁶
               = 1.5 × 10¹⁷ bytes
               ÷ (1024⁵ bytes/PB)
               ≈ 133 Petabytes
```

### Crawl Rate (QPS)
```
1 billion pages/month
= 10⁹ / (30 days × 24 hrs × 3600 sec)
= 10⁹ / 2,592,000
≈ 385 pages/second
```

> **Interview insight:** Always calculate both storage AND throughput. Storage tells you how much hardware you need; throughput tells you how much parallelism you need.

