## Deep Dive: URL Frontier

The URL Frontier is the brain of the crawler — it decides what to crawl and when.

### Two-Level Queue Architecture

```
Incoming URLs
     │
     ▼
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│       Priority Queues        │
│  Q1 (high priority) ────►   │
│  Q2 (medium priority) ──►   │  ← Prioritiser assigns scores
│  Q3 (low priority) ─────►   │
└─────────────┬───────────────┘
              │
              ▼
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│       Politeness Queues      │
│  bbc.com queue     ────►    │
│  cnn.com queue     ────►    │  ← One queue per domain
│  reddit.com queue  ────►    │    with time delay enforced
└─────────────┬───────────────┘
              │
              ▼
         Worker Threads
```

**Priority scoring factors:**
- PageRank (how many sites link to this page?)
- Update frequency (how often does this page change?)
- Domain authority (is this a trusted, authoritative site?)

**Politeness enforcement:**
- Each domain has a dedicated sub-queue
- A router ensures workers only pull from a domain queue if the last request to that domain was more than N seconds ago
- This respects `Crawl-delay` settings in `robots.txt`

